INSERT INTO `tbl_cms` VALUES (1,'Work Integrated Learning Portal','[h1]Introduction[/h1][p]\nThe Department of Co-operative Education is responsible for the placement of students in industry and the management of work integrated learning at the University. [br]The management of work integrated learning involves managing the placement of students, managing the academic departments in the supervision and monitoring of students, quality assuring the monitoring and assessments of students engaged in work integrated learning, ensuring that student\'s portfolios and progress reports are properly managed, ensuring that work integrated learning is appropriately structured, ensuring that employer work stations are accredited and certified, ensuring that the all students and Mentors complete a Feedback Report at the end of the training period, ensuring that the Feedback Report is used in the curriculum development and quality management processes of the University. [br]The WIL Portal generates Operational System Alerts to remind all Users of the tasks that are due.  If a User ignores any deadlines, the Portal generates Supervisory System Alerts for the attention of the Management of Co-operative Education. [/p]\n[b]The Work Integrated Learning Portal[/b]\n[p]The University Work Integrated Learning Portal facilitates the management of work integrated learning and student placement by providing an online interface between the Department of Cooperative Education, the Academic Departments, University Academics, Employers, Mentors and Students.  [br]This interface is supported by the Online University Management System (OLUMS) which links the information from the University database with that of the management processes of work integrated learning.[br]The online management system manages the recruitment of students and the management of work integrated learning.   [/p]\n[list][*]    Student Placement Management System[/*][*]    Work Integrated Learning Management System[/*][/list]\n[h2]1. Student Placement Management System[/h2]\n[p][b]Employers[/b][/p]\n[p][b]Employers can perform the following functions online:[/b][/p]\n[list][*]    Post advertisements and search the search the University database for students.[/*][*]    Shortlist students[/*][*]    Schedule Interviews[/*][*]    Make Job offers[/*][*]    Provide feedback to the University community[/*][/list]\n[p][b]Students[/b][/p]\n[p][b]Students can[/b][/p]\n[list][*]    Update their Profile[/*][*]    Upload their CVs[/*][*]    Search for jobs posted by the Employers[/*][*]    Apply online for jobs[/*][*]    Receive sms and email alerts of Job Interviews[/*][*]    Confirm their availability for interviews[/*][*]    View all the placement activities via their individual Dashboard Menu[/*][/list]\n[b]University[/b]\n[p]The Co-operative Education Department of the University supervises and manages all placement activities between the employer and the student. [/p]\n[h2] 2. Work Integrated Learning[/h2]\n[b]Employer[/b]\n[p]The Employer assigns a Mentor to supervise, guide and coach the students during their work integrated learning experience at the workplace. [/p]\n[p]The Work Integrated Learning Portal a user friendly management system that provides online access to Employers and Mentor to manage students engaged in work integrated learning.[/p]\n[p]The Mentor and the Academic Assessor collaborates in the assessment of the student\'s performance.  The Mentor can monitor and assess the student\'s progress and provide feedback to the Academic Assessor and Student. [/p]\n[p]Upon completion of the work integrated learning training, Mentors and Students completes Feedback Reports on curriculum issues.  These Reports are collated and presented to the respective Departments for consideration during the curriculum review process.[/p]\n[p][b]Student[/b][/p]\n[p]Students have online access to continuously submit progress reports and upload supporting documents, conduct self assessments and provide feedback to the Mentors and Academic Assessors in real time.  [/p]\n[p]The student can view in real time, all the Mentor\'s and Academic Assessor\'s comments and assessment of tasks completed by the student. [/p]\n[p] At the end of the work integrated learning training, students provide feedback to the University on curriculum and performance related issues. These feedback reports are an essential component to improving the quality and relevance of the qualifications offered by the University.[/p]\n[p][b]Academic Assessor[/b][/p]\n[p]The University appoints an Academic Assessor to monitor and assess students engaged in work integrated learning. [/p]\n[p]The Academic Assessor is also responsible for approving the Employer workstations and conducting onsite visitations to monitor the student\'s performance.[/p]\n[p][b]The Academic Assessor performs the following functions online:[/b][/p]\n[p]Approval of the student work integrated learning registration; assessment of student\'s progress reports; gives feedback to students and Mentors; plans onsite the visitation schedule; completes onsite visitation report; receives work integrated learning portfolio; receives student and Mentor feedback report.[/p]\n[p][b]Department of Co-operative Education[/b][/p]\n[p]The Co-operative Education Department of the University monitors and follows up on all non-compliance of work integrated learning activities, manages the Certification of Accredited Employers, tracks all students who are ready for WIL placement, tracks the graduation of students who had completed WIL, tracks the WIL statistics per qualification in the format as required by professional councils and bodies such as the Engineering Council of SA and the Council on Higher Education.[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-10-27 20:58:42','index','/img/img-banner.jpg'),(2,'FAQ\'S','<p>\r\n	Coming Soon ... ... ...</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>',3,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-02-11 21:08:26','faq',''),(3,'More About Sign On','<p>\r\n	Coming Soon .. .. .. ..</p>\r\n',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-01-21 13:05:41',NULL,''),(4,'Help','<p>\r\n	Coming soon</p>\r\n',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-09-13 01:10:56',NULL,''),(5,'Student Guidelines','[h1]PART 1: UNDERSTANDING WBE[/h1][p]Welcome to workplace-based experience (WBE). For many of you this will be your first real exposure to a workplace in the field in which you are training. We hope that this will be a valuable experience for you. To gain the full benefit from your experience, though, you must make the most of your time in the workplace. Take the opportunity to learn as much as you can about how your host employer operates and the kind of work your course is preparing you to do. Remember, you will learn best by asking questions and, whenever possible, taking part in workplace tasks. The diagram below provides ideas on how you can get the most out of your work placement.[/p]\r\n[h1]PART 2: PREPARATION AND WBE FORMS[/h1][h2]Instructions to prepare for WBE[/h2][p]Before you start your WBE you need to make sure ALL 4 administrative forms are completed and signed, if necessary, by you, your guardian (if you are under 18), the college and the employer. Ask your lecturer/WBE mentor to check the forms before you go into the workplace.[/p][p]You also need to complete other important preparation tasks:[/p][p]if you are under 18, give your parent/guardian the letter from your college about your WBE placement (letter to be provided by your college).[/p][p]With the assistance of your college, make transport arrangements to get to your host employer.[/p][p]Find out about your host employer????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??º??????s dress code and/or personal protective equipment (PPE) requirements. Make sure you are able to comply. Obtain the personal protective equipment (PPE) required, if necessary.[/p][h1]PART 3 ????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??«????? SECTION A: GENERAL ACTIVITIES[/h1][p]Activities 1 to 3 make up 50% of your total assessment for practical task 2. Instructions to complete the activities are included with each activity.[/p][h2]It is compulsory to complete the following BEFORE you leave the workplace:[/h2][p]The section A attendance and activity approval page (you MUST get the supervisor????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??º??????s signature in both tables).\r\nAll pages of the Log and Journal (activity 2).\r\nThe section A attendance register and activity approval table (on the next page) has two tables:\r\nThe attendance register, which needs to be signed daily by the student and the supervisor.\r\nThe host employer approval of section A activities. On the last day of your work placement, once you have completed activities 1 to 3, ask your supervisor to check and sign this section. Your supervisor????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??º??????s signature means you have either completed the activities satisfactorily or obtained all the information you need to complete any outstanding questions when back at college.[/p]\r\n[h1]PART 4: CONFIRMATION AND EVALUATION OF WBE[/h1][h2]Instructions to complete Part 4:[/h2]\r\n[p]The confirmation of WBE and evaluation takes place once you have finished the WBE placement. Some of the documents need to be completed before you leave the workplace and others when back at the college.\r\nBefore you leave the host employer[/p][p]Make sure you have the completed the Employer Confirmation letter and the Employer Evaluation:[/p]\r\n[p]The Employer Confirmation Letter confirms your placement with the employer and indicates what work experience you received. This will assist you to get employment in the future. Make sure that your employer stamps the top of the letter.\r\nThe Employer Evaluation provides the opportunity for your host employer to evaluate your performance during your placement. You need to make sure that this is completed by your host employer before you leave the workplace.[/p]\r\n[p]When back at the college[/p]\r\n[p]Evaluate your WBE by completing the Student Evaluation in full.[/p][p]Your last steps before you leave your employer[/p][p]Remember you cannot easily go back to your host employer. Make sure you have a completed confirmation letter and evaluation from your employer BEFORE you leave. Also do a final check to see that you have all the information and signatures you need.[/p][p]Remember to thank your employer in person when you leave and in writing ????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??«????? it is a good idea to send an email of thanks.[/p]\r\n\r\n[h1]PART 5: ASSESSMENT[/h1][p]Instructions to assess the workplace-based experience practical 2 tasks[/p][p]In total there are FOUR assessment rubrics, which together provide a mark for practical task 2 for each vocational subject and the optional subject.[/p][p]Section A is assessed using ONE rubric, found at the end of section A.[/p][p]Each activity in section B is assessed using a subject specific rubric, found at the end of each activity. There are THREE section B rubrics.[/p][p]Section Rubric Activity assessed Subject assessed[/p][p]For More Information [link= /index/download-document/ajax/2/type/1/cms_id/student][b]Download[/b][/link][/p]',0,'','/documents/student_guidelines.pdf',1,'2015-06-16 15:40:59','2011-04-25 00:39:35','student',''),(6,'Employer & Mentor Guidelines','[h1]INTRODUCING WORKPLACE-BASED EXPERIENCE[/h1][p]Thank you for agreeing to host an FET college student for his/her workplace-based experience (WBE) at your organisation. WBE is about providing students with short periods of exposure (usually 5 to 15 days) in a real workplace and the opportunity to work alongside employees doing jobs related to their field of study.[/p]\r\n[h2]The employer\'s role in assisting the student in completing the task book:[/h2]\r\n[p]This guide will outline how, as an employer, you can prepare to host the student and assist the student to get the most from his/her experience. As an employer, you are kindly requested to complete six broad functions:\r\nBefore looking at each of these functions in detail it is useful to understand the structure of the task book.[/p]\r\n[p][/p][h2]The structure of the task book.[/h2][p]PART 1 An overview of the student\'s programme as well as instructions to complete the WBE.[/p][p]PART 2 The administrative forms that need to be completed.[/p][p]PART 3 This is the core of the task book and contains the workplace activities the student should complete.[/p][p]PART 4 A set of evaluation documents and an employer letter to confirm placement.[/p][p]PART 5 An explanation of how assessment works (the assessment is the college????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??º??????s responsibility).[/p]\r\n[h2]Provide an induction[/h2][p]As an employer you will be involved in some administrative aspects of part 2 and part 4. However, your largest involvement will be in part 3 where students are required to complete workplace tasks linked to the requirements of their particular subject.[/p]\r\n[p]Please refer to the diagram on the next page. The diagram provides details on what is included in parts 2 to 5 of the task book on a single page the entire task book at a glance. The before, during and after buttons in the diagram refer to when students will mostly be working on each part of their book, i.e. before, during or after their WBE placement.[/p]\r\n[p]Assign a mentor\r\nConduct admin at the start of the placement\r\nPrepare a work schedule\r\nConfirm placement and evaluate student performance\r\nProvide opportunities for students to complete activities and verify completion[/p][p]For More Information[link=/index/download-document/ajax/2/type/1/cms_id/employer] [b]Download[/b][/link][/p]',0,'','/documents/employer_guidelines.pdf',1,'2015-06-16 15:42:21','2014-02-03 01:34:19','employer',''),(7,'Coordinator Guidelines','[h1]TVET COLLEGE LECTURER GUIDE[/h1][p][/p][h2][b]Part 1:[/b]Understanding WBE[/h2][p]An introduction to WBE and consists of:[/p][p]In creating student understanding of, and enthusiasm for, WBE it is important that lecturers provide a clear overview of WBE from the start. Lecturers should use the notes in part 1 to provide a broad definition of WBE and focus on the three key phases of the WBE:[/p][p]before placement,[/p][p]during placement (what happens at the workplace),[/p][p]and after placement.[/p][p]It is vital that students understand what is expected of them in each of the WBE phases. As lecturers have a key role in briefing and preparing students for WBE, an overview of each phase is provided below.[/p][p][/p][h2][b]Part 2:[/b] Fill out WBE forms[/h2][p]Part 2 contains four administrative forms that need to be completed by students.[/p][p]Provide students with the following instructions:[/p][p]Remind students that ALL 4 administrative forms need to be completed and signed by themselves, their guardian (if under 18), the college and the employer.[/p][p]Explain that completing the forms ensures that all arrangements are in place by the time they arrive at the workplace which means that they can start learning and working straight away.[/p][h2][b]Part 3:[/b] WBE PLACEMENT Complete activities [/h2][p]Part 3 contains all the activities that need to be completed as part of the WBE and ICASS[/p][p]practical task 2. This is the CORE of the task book and the student must complete ALL of these activities.[/p][p]It is important that students understand that each section counts for 50% of their ICASS practical task 2.[/p][h2][b]Part 4:[/b] CONFIRMATION AND COMPLETE EVALUATION OF WBE\r\n[/h2]\r\n[p]PART 4: CONFIRMATION AND EVALUATION OF WBE[/p][p]Part 4 is an important administrative part of the WBE as it confirms that students did participate in WBE and evaluates their performance.[/p][p]The following forms need to be completed in Part 4. Please ensure that students know what needs to be completed before they leave the workplace.[/p][p]Evaluation form / letter Why the form is included in the task book[/p][p]Employer letter to confirm student work experience[/p][p]This letter simply acts as confirmation that the WBE was successfully completed. The student needs to ensure that the employer has completed the letter before leaving the workplace.[/p][p]Remind students to attach this letter to their CVs when looking for a job.[/p][p]Employer evaluation of student[/p][p]The employer evaluation evaluates student performance during the placement. It is used as evidence in the assessment, but more importantly can be used by students as a resource to seek employment in the future.[/p][p]Students need to ensure that the employer has completed the evaluation before they leave the workplace. In some instances the employer may commit to email or fax the evaluation to the lecturer/WBE coordinator. If this is the case, students must ensure that the lecturer has received the form. If not, students should phone the employer and respectfully request the form.[/p][p]Again, remind students that the evaluation can be attached to their CVs.[/p][p]Student evaluation of WBE[/p][p]This is a self-evaluation, giving students the opportunity to rate different aspects of the WBE, including preparation for WBE; the connection between WBE and their programme of study; what was valuable about the process, etc.[/p][p][/p][h2][b]Part 5:[/b] The assessment\r\n[/h2][p]The way in which the assessment rubric is structured and the instructions to assess the task book are clearly detailed at the end of each task book. A brief overview is provided here.[/p][p]In total there are FOUR assessment rubrics which together provide a mark for practical task 2 for each vocational subject and the optional subject.[/p][p]Section A is assessed using ONE rubric which is found at the end of section A.[/p][p]Each activity in section B is assessed using a subject-specific rubric which is found at the end of each activity. There are THREE section B rubrics.[/p][p]Each subject lecturer marks his/her subject activity in section B. As a group, you will need to decide how to mark section A. In some colleges the programme manager marks section A for all students; in other colleges, lecturers divide the books and each mark an equal amount of section A. You will need to discuss as a team what will work best in your college.[/p][p]Using the rubric[/p][p]Each rubric clearly stipulates the assessment criteria linked to each question in the activity. Marks are allocated for each criterion (and sub-items of a criterion). You will see the table has a column for ????????????Â??º??ú??????????possible mark per question????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??º?????? and a column for ????????????Â??º??ú??????????mark achieved by student????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??º??????.[/p][p]In the rubric ????????????Â??º??ú??????????tick icons????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??º?????? show how many marks are allocated to each part of a question. Tick the questions in the activity and carefully transfer these marks to the assessment rubic, checking your calculations for each question against the possible marks the student can achieve for the particular question.[/p][p]When marking a particular activity be sure to assess the accuracy and degree of completion of each question, but also be sure to assess the level of effort, analysis and thought that the student has provided. The student cannot get full marks merely for completing the particular question.[/p][p]Once you have marked your activity please pass the book onto the next lecturer to ensure that all activities get marked as quickly as possible.[/p][p]The mark given for each subject consists of two marks ????????????Â??º??ú????????Â??«????? a mark for section A (50%) and a mark for the activity for the subject concerned in section B (50%).[/p][p]For More Information [link=/index/download-document/ajax/2/type/1/cms_id/university][b]Download[/b][/link][/p]',0,'','/documents/academic_policy.pdf',1,'2015-06-16 15:23:29','2013-06-21 03:31:20','university',''),(8,'Welcome To The Work Integrated Learning Portal','[h1]Placement system[/h1]\r\n[p]The Portal allows the student to apply for jobs posted on the Portal, view the status of their applications, view the interview schedules, view the results of the and view the results of the interviews.[/p]\r\n[p]Employers can also search for Portal for students, invite students for interviews, schedule interviews, and provide feedback to students[/p]\r\n[b]Work Integrated Learning system[/b]\r\n[p]Students can view the qualification outcomes, submit progress reports, view assessments, communicate with Mentors and University Academics, and provide feedback to the University[/p]\r\n[b]To register for Work Integrated Learning:[/b]\r\n[p][b]Step 1[/b]  Goto the \"[b]Work Intergrated Learning\"[/b] Menu\r\n[b]Step 2[/b]  Click on \"[b]WIL Registration[/b]\"\r\n[b]Step 3[/b]  Click on \"[b][/b][b]New Registration[/b]\"[/p]\r\n[p]General information on work integrated learning can be viewed at www.universityportal.co.za[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-09-12 03:25:00','student_dashboard',''),(9,'Welcome Employer','[h1]WELCOME TO THE WORK INTEGRATED LEARNING ONLINE MANAGEMENT SYSTEM[/h1]\r\n[p]The Employers provide training opportunities to students requiring work integrated learning experience.  Employer s with permission from the University, can access the Online University Management System (OLUMS) which will allow employer to recruit students and manage all the processes of work integrated learning online and in a user friendly environment.[/p]\r\n[p]Employers can search for students, place job advertisements, shortlist students for interview, schedule interviews, make job offers and provide feedback to students online.[/p]\r\n[p]All University students have access to OLUMS with personalized Dashboards.  They will receive Dashboard Alerts, Smses Alerts and Email Alerts when they are selected for interviews, when jobs offers are made, when engaged in work integrated learning processes, etc.[/p]\r\n[b]Employer Contacts [/b]\r\n[p]Several personnel can be linked to a single Employer as employer contacts.  Mentors and Human Resources Managers are examples of employer contacts.[/p]\r\n[b]Employer Branch[/b]\r\n[p]If an Employer has more than one branch, then the unique branch name must be included in the name of the branch e.g. Siemens Mobile, Midrand[/p]\r\n[b]Employer Accreditation[/b]\r\n[p]Employers are required to be accredited by the University before engaging students for  Work Integrated Learning.  The Employer needs to ensure that the workstations are adequately resourced to meet the learning outcomes of the qualification and a suitably experienced and qualified Mentor is available to supervise and assess the student.  The University will assist and guide the Employer through the accreditation process.[/p]\r\n[b]Mentor[/b]\r\n[p]The Employer must appoint a Mentor to guide and coach the student throughout the training period.  The Mentor will also assist in assessment of the student\'s progress.  The Mentor prepares a learning program which is a list of tasks that the student is required to complete in order to meet the work integrated learning outcomes. The Academic Department will provide guidance in this regard.[/p]\r\n[h2]CONTACT US[/h2]\r\n[p]If you have any queries or any suggestions which will make OLUMS more friendlier, please feel free to contact us anytime[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-02-03 01:37:22','employer_dashboard',''),(10,'WELCOME TO SETA GRANT MANAGEMENT SYSTEM','[p][b]SETA GRANT MANAGEMENT SYSTEM[/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]WHAT PURPOSE OF SETA GRANTS[/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]THE ROLE OF THE LEAD EMPLOYER (MAIN)[/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]THE ROLE OF THE HOST EMPLOYERS (SECONDARY)[/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]THE ROLE OF THE STUDENTS[/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]HOW TO CONTACT US? Chat + Contact us TO LEAD EMPLOYER ADMIN (MAIN)[/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]HOW TO COMPLETE THE SETA FORMS>SETA 1, SETA 2, SETA 3, [/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]LIBRARY OF SETA; BRANCHES\r\n[/b][/p]',5,'','',1,'2015-06-16 09:47:30','2014-02-03 01:46:52','university_dashboard',''),(11,'Industrial Mentor','[b]Mentor[/b]\r\n[p]The Employer must appoint a Mentor to guide and coach the student throughout the training period. The Mentor will also assist in assessment of the student\'s progress. One Mentor can be appointed for more than one student. The Mentor prepares a learning program which is a list of tasks that the student is required to complete in order to meet the work integrated learning outcomes. The Academic Department will provide guidance in this regard.[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-06-26 01:18:44','mentor_dashboard',''),(12,'Privacy Policy and Guidelines','<p> OLUMS built the OLUMS SETA Portal app as a Free app. This SERVICE is provided by\n                    OLUMS at no cost and is intended for use as is.\n                  </p> <p>This page is used to inform visitors regarding our policies with the collection, use, and disclosure\n                    of Personal Information if anyone decided to use our Service.\n                  </p> <p>If you choose to use our Service, then you agree to the collection and use of information in\n                    relation to this policy. The Personal Information that we collect is used for providing and improving\n                    the Service. We will not use or share your information with anyone except as described\n                    in this Privacy Policy.\n                  </p> <p>The terms used in this Privacy Policy have the same meanings as in our Terms and Conditions, which is\n                    accessible at OLUMS SETA Portal unless otherwise defined in this Privacy Policy.\n                  </p> <p><strong>Information Collection and Use</strong></p> <p>For a better experience, while using our Service, we may require you to provide us with certain\n                    personally identifiable information, including but not limited to Location of Learners at the time of Attendance Marking, Location of Workstation for Supervisors. The information that we request will be retained by us and used as described in this privacy policy.\n                  </p> <p>The app does use third party services that may collect information used to identify you.</p> <div><p>Link to privacy policy of third party service providers used by the app</p> <ul><li><a href=\"https://www.google.com/policies/privacy/\" target=\"_blank\">Google Play Services</a></li><!----><li><a href=\"https://firebase.google.com/policies/analytics\" target=\"_blank\">Firebase Analytics</a></li><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----></ul></div> <p><strong>Log Data</strong></p> <p> We want to inform you that whenever you use our Service, in a case of\n                    an error in the app we collect data and information (through third party products) on your phone\n                    called Log Data. This Log Data may include information such as your device Internet Protocol (\"IP\") address,\n                    device name, operating system version, the configuration of the app when utilizing our Service,\n                    the time and date of your use of the Service, and other statistics.\n                  </p> <p><strong>Cookies</strong></p> <p>Cookies are files with a small amount of data that are commonly used as anonymous unique identifiers.\n                    These are sent to your browser from the websites that you visit and are stored on your device\'s internal\n                    memory.\n                  </p> <p>This Service does not use these \"cookies\" explicitly. However, the app may use third party code and\n                    libraries that use \"cookies\" to collect information and improve their services. You have the option to\n                    either accept or refuse these cookies and know when a cookie is being sent to your device. If you choose\n                    to refuse our cookies, you may not be able to use some portions of this Service.\n                  </p> <p><strong>Service Providers</strong></p> <p> We may employ third-party companies and individuals due to the following reasons:</p> <ul><li>To facilitate our Service;</li> <li>To provide the Service on our behalf;</li> <li>To perform Service-related services; or</li> <li>To assist us in analyzing how our Service is used.</li></ul> <p> We want to inform users of this Service that these third parties have access to\n                    your Personal Information. The reason is to perform the tasks assigned to them on our behalf. However,\n                    they are obligated not to disclose or use the information for any other purpose.\n                  </p> <p><strong>Security</strong></p> <p> We value your trust in providing us your Personal Information, thus we are striving\n                    to use commercially acceptable means of protecting it. But remember that no method of transmission over\n                    the internet, or method of electronic storage is 100% secure and reliable, and we cannot guarantee\n                    its absolute security.\n                  </p> <p><strong>Links to Other Sites</strong></p> <p>This Service may contain links to other sites. If you click on a third-party link, you will be directed\n                    to that site. Note that these external sites are not operated by us. Therefore, we strongly\n                    advise you to review the Privacy Policy of these websites. We have no control over\n                    and assume no responsibility for the content, privacy policies, or practices of any third-party sites\n                    or services.\n                  </p> <p><strong>Children\'s Privacy</strong></p> <p>These Services do not address anyone under the age of 13. We do not knowingly collect\n                    personally identifiable information from children under 13. In the case we discover that a child\n                    under 13 has provided us with personal information, we immediately delete this from\n                    our servers. If you are a parent or guardian and you are aware that your child has provided us with personal\n                    information, please contact us so that we will be able to do necessary actions.\n                  </p> <p><strong>Changes to This Privacy Policy</strong></p> <p> We may update our Privacy Policy from time to time. Thus, you are advised to review\n                    this page periodically for any changes. We will notify you of any changes by posting\n                    the new Privacy Policy on this page. These changes are effective immediately after they are posted on\n                    this page.\n                  </p>',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-03-24 23:19:17','policy_and_guidelines',''),(13,'Term & Condtion','[h1]Durban University of Technology[/h1]\r\n[h2]Terms and Conditions[/h2]\r\n[p][u][b]NOTE: YOUR REGISTRATION WILL NOT BE FINALISED UNLESS THIS UNDERTAKING AND INDEMINITY IS ACCEPTED. [/b][/u][/p]\r\n[list=1][*][p]By my acceptance hereto, I fully understand and accept that upon registration I will attend the Durban University of Technology (hereafter referred to as the DUT) and undertake all activities at the DUT entirely at my own risk.  I agree that DUT\'s liability to me, my estate, my dependants or any other person in respect of any claims arising from loss or damage to property owned by me or in my possession or under my control or from bodily injury to me or from my death shall be limited to the extent to which such claims are covered and met by DUT\'s insurance.  Thus, save to the extent that any claim (or part thereof) may be covered and met by DUT\'s insurance.  I hereby release, indemnify and absolve the DUT, its Council, its staff, its agents, representatives and all persons for whom it is vicariously liable against any and all claims whatsoever which claims may be made by me, my estate, my dependants or any other person arising from loss or damage to property owned by me or in my possession or under my control or from bodily injury to me or my death regardless of the nature or cause of such loss, damage, injury or death and regardless of whether it be caused by the negligent act or omission of the DUT, its Council, its staff, its agents, representatives or other persons for whom it is vicariously liable.  I understand the nature and extent of this release.[/p][/*][*][p] I shall, whilst a registered student, abide by all the rules and regulations of the DUT currently in force and as amended from time to time.[/p][/*][*][p] I undertake to make payment of all fees and charges on or before the date upon which payment thereof is finally due, and I otherwise accept and undertake to abide by the conditions relating to payment of fees and charges and deregistration.  Should I fail to make timeous payment DUT shall be entitled to charge, and I accept liability to pay, interest on the amount due at the prevailing interest rate applicable to incidental credit agreements from time to time as provided for in the National Credit Act, 34 of 2005, as amended and published in the DUT fees book.[/p][/*][*][p] I understand and accept that if fees and/or any other monies I owe to the DUT are not paid in full and/or library books and/or other property on loan from the DUT and are not returned then, notwithstanding anything to the contrary, the DUT reserves the right to, inter alia, withhold my examination results until such time as I fully meet these commitments.[/p][/*][*][p] I undertake to pay all legal costs incurred by the DUT as between attorney and own client, including collection charges, if any, with regard to instructions given by the DUT to it\'s attorney for the recovery of any arrear fees and/or other charges due irrespective of whether or not legal action is actually instituted against me.[/p][/*][*][p] I understand and accept that non-attendance of the academic programme by me for any reason whatsoever does not absolve me from making full payment of the full programme fees and does not entitle me to claim any refund of or reduction in the academic programme fees which may already have been paid.[/p][/*][*][p] I am aware that my registration may be cancelled by the DUT if such registration fails in any way to comply with the regulations of the DUT.[/p][/*][*][p] I have read and fully understood the [u][b]Work Integrated Learning Policy[/b][/u] of the Durban University of Technology, and that I shall fully comply with the [u][b]Work Integrated Learning Policy[/b][/u] and requirements therein.[/p][/*][*][p] I warrant and declare that all information and particulars furnished in the registration are true and correct.  I hereby acknowledge that a breach of this warranty constitutes a material breach of the agreement which will entitle the DUT, without prejudice to any other rights or remedies which it may have, to cancel my registration at the DUT.[/p][/*][/list]\r\n[p][u][i][b]I have read and understood and accept the above undertaking and the Work Integrated Learning Policy of the Durban University of Technology.[/b][/i][/u][/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-09-13 00:57:25','Term',''),(14,'Student Search History Activation Deactivation','[p]It is a long established fact that a reader will be distracted by the readable content of a page when looking at its layout.[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-03-27 22:37:17','StudentSearchHistory',''),(15,'What is work integrated learning?','[p]Work integrated learning is a variety of educational activities that integrate theoretical learning with its application in the workplace. These educational activities should provide a meaningful experience of the workplace application that is intentional, organized and recognized by the University, in order for the student to achieve the learning outcomes of the qualification for which the student is registered for.[/p]\r\n[p]Several qualifications offered at Universities include periods of learning that takes place at the workplace with an employer. The work integrated learning is structured and supervised by a mentor appointed by the employer. The University academics are responsible for the supervising the student during their work integrated learning. The supervision includes approving the Employer Work station, conducting on site visitation, and assessment of the work integrated learning portfolio. [/p]\r\n[p]Examples of University qualifications that include work integrated learning are the Diplomas in Electrical Engineering, Electronic Engineering, Computer Systems Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, Mechatronics Engineering, Industrial Engineering, Chemical Engineering, Civil Engineering, etc [/p]\r\n[p]The duration of study for the above qualifications is 3 years. The student spends two years of studies at the University and one year of work integrated learning at the workplace of the Employer.[/p]',4,'2','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:16:29','integratedlearning',''),(16,'What is the role of the Employer?','[h1]Employer[/h1]\r\n[p]The Employer is responsible for appointing the student, appointing Mentors to supervise the student, developing a training program for the student to follow, and ensuring that the work place is approved by the University for the specific qualifications.[/p]',4,'2','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:31:47','EmployerRole',''),(17,'What is the role of the Mentor?','[p]A Mentor is a suitably qualified and experienced person who is responsible for:[/p][list][*][b]Coaching [/b]and  [b]mentoring [/b]the student during the training period[/*][*]Assessing the students performance[/*][*]Developing a Training Program in consultation with the University Academic[/*][*]Providing feedback to the University[/*][/list]',4,'2','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:50:10','MentorRole',''),(18,'What is the role of the University Assessor?','[h1]University Assessor[/h1]\r\n[list][*]The University Assessor is an academic employed by the University for specific programs.[/*][*]The University Assessor is responsible for[/*][*]integrated learning registration with the University[/*][*]Assisting the employers to develop work integrated learning training programs[/*][*]Assessing and approving employer workstations for certification.[/*][*]Providing assistance and guidance to the students during their training.[/*][*]Regular on site monitoring and assessment of student\'s performance.[/*][*]Assessing student\'s progress reports and providing regular feedback to students and mentor.[/*][/list]',4,'2','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:35:27','UniversityAssessor',''),(19,'What is work place approval?','[h1]Workplace Approval[/h1]\r\n[p]Employers that engage in the training of work integrated learning students must ensure that the training workstations are approved by the respective University prior to the commencement of any training. Approval of workstations is qualification specific. This means that each qualification would require independent approvals.[/p]\r\n[p]The requirements for workplace approval are as follows:[/p]\r\n[list][*]Appropriate resources[/*][*]Suitably qualified and experienced Mentors[/*][*]A training program[/*][*]Appropriate resources[/*][*]Employer needs to demonstrate that the resources required for the student to achieve the work integrated learning outcomes, are available and accessible. The resources would include appropriate tools and equipment, appropriate facilities, operational plants, etc[/*][*]It is possible that some work integrated learning outcomes cannot be achieved at the employer\'s workplace. Examples of these are hand skills training, health and safety training, etc. In this case, the employer can make the necessary arrangements to send the students to other outside training facilities in order to achieve these outcomes.[/*][/list]\r\n[p][i]After a workstation is approved, the University shall issue a Certificate of Approval valid of 3 years.[/i][/p]\r\n[p][i]Employers requiring assistance in-order to become compliant as an Approved Employer, should contact the University in the [CONTACT US] menu.[/i][/p]',4,'2','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:38:10','approval',''),(20,'What is a training program?','[h1]WIL Training program[/h1]\r\n[p]A Training program is a list of tasks that the students will be assigned during their work integrated learning training.  [/p]\r\n[list][*]Each task will have a title and a brief description of the task.[/*][*]Each task should include the approximate time that it the student will spend on it, e.g., 1 day, 5 days, 3 weeks, etc.[/*][*]Each Task is linked to one or more outcomes of the formal qualification.[/*][*]The duration of all the tasks will be added together to ensure compliance with the total duration of the work integrated learning period.  For example the duration of P1 is 6 months or 24 weeks.  Each week comprises 5 days. [/*][*]Mentors are advised to consult with the Academic Assessors when developing a training program[/*][/list]\r\n[h2]Example of a Training Program[/h2]',4,'2','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:40:59','trainingprogram',''),(21,'What are Learning Outcomes?','[p]Learning Outcomes are concerned with the achievements of the learner rather than the intentions of the teacher. (Adam, 2004)[/p]\r\n[p]University of Exeter (2004) defines Learning Outcome as: \r\nAn expression of what a student will demonstrate on the successful completion of a module. [/p]\r\n[list][*]Learning outcomes: are related to the level of the learning;[/*][*]indicate the intended gain in knowledge and skills that a typical student will achieve[/*][*]should be capable of being assessed.[/*][/list]',4,'2','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:43:11','LearningOutcomes',''),(22,'How does an Employer apply to have their Work Station approved?','[p]The Employer registers onto the WIL PORTAL and chooses the qualifications for which approval is requested and simply request for work station approval.  This request will be directed to the relevant Academic who is linked to the qualification.  The Academic then engages with the Employer and conducts an on site visitation for approval of the work station.\r\n[/p]',4,'2','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:44:10','WorkStationapproved',''),(23,'Coach','[b]Coach[/b]\r\n[p]An expert on people and personal development. Typically a skilled specialist regarding a certain topic, competency, or industry. A coach\'s role is to provide structure, foundation, and support so people can begin to self-generate the results they want on their own. Coaching is a process of inquiry, relying on the use on well crafted questions, rather than continually sharing the answer to get people to sharpen their own problem solving skills. Learning and growth are achieved by both parties involved. In coaching, the relationship is objective, and the focus is not only on what the person needs to do to become more successful but also who the person is and how he thinks. A coach works on the whole person and is multidimensional, rather than focusing only on what the person is already doing. The coaching relationship is built on choice rather than necessity.[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:46:43','Coach',''),(24,'Mentor','[b]Mentor[/b]\r\n[p]An expert in a field, industry, or at a company who typically acts as an internal advisor. Usually this is done on a professional level to advance the mentored person\'s career. Often mentors have their own approach already in mind and use the system that has worked for them in the past, without taking into consideration the style, values, integrity, or strengths of the people they mentor. As such, the mentor offers more solutions and answers to the person they mentor, rather than questions that challenge people to change their thinking and behavior; making this more of a one way, training-driven vs. collaborative (coaching) relationship. Mentors may also have something to gain professionally and, as such, have their own personal agenda. Often, mentors are not trained, and their guidance is based more on their experience rather than the skills or proficiencies needed to mentor. Often, the mentoring relationship is need-driven rather than driven by choice.[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-14 03:48:01','Mentor',''),(25,'Online Registration','[h1]WELCOME TO THE DURBAN UNIVERSITY OF TECHNOLOGY ONLINE WORK INTEGRATED LEARNING REGISTRATION SYSTEM.[/h1]\r\n[h2]Step 1      Student details[/h2]\r\n[p]Upon logging onto the online system.  Students will be required to update their email address, their physical address, home telephone number and their mobile number[/p]\r\n[h2]Step 2      Qualification details[/h2]\r\n[p][b]Campus:[/b]  Choose the Durban or Pietermaritzburg Campus from the pull down menu[/p]\r\n[p][b]Subject name:[/b] Chose P1 or P2[/p]\r\n[p][b]Start Date: End Date: [/b]\r\nEnter the start date of the training.  The is automatically calculated.  The end date can be edited.[/p]\r\n[h2]Step 3      Employer Details[/h2][b][p]Name of the Employer:[/p][/b]\r\n[p]Students must choose the Employer from the drop down list if the employer is already registered with the University.  If the Employer does not exist on the system, then the student must [b]ADD NEW EMPLOYER[/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]Branch name[/b][/p][p]If the Employer has several branches and each branch operates as an independent business unit, then the Branch Name that uniquely identifies the Branch from other Branches of the Employer must be included.  Otherwise, the Branch Name is optional[/p]\r\n[p][b]For example:[/b][/p]\r\n[p][b]Name of Employer:[/b] SIEMENS PTY LTD[/p]\r\n[p][b]Branch Name:[/b]      Nokia Siemens[/p]\r\n[p]Nokia Siemens branch of Siemens PTY LTD will be treated as an independent employer if this branch operates as an independent business unit.  Accordingly, if a Branch of Siemens does not exist, then the new Branch must be added as a NEW EMPLOYER.[/p]\r\n[b]Physical Address[/b]\r\n[p]This Physical address is the main address of the administration section of the Employer This physical address is not necessarily the address at which the work integrated learning training will be conducted.[/p][h2]Step 4      Mentor Details[/h2]\r\n[p]Students must enter the name, email adress and mobile number of the mentor[/p]\r\n[h2]Step 5      Work Station Address[/h2]\r\n[p]This is the actual address where the student will receive all his/her training.  The student must keep the University informed of changes to the Workstation locations at all times by activating the correct work station address if the student is transferred to another location.  The student must select the Work Station Address from the Pull Down list.  If the Workstation Address does not exit then the student must ADD NEW WORKSTATION[/p]\r\n[h2]Step 6      Fee Details[/h2]\r\n[p]Comming soon............[/p]\r\n[h2]Step 7      Acceptance Of University Policy[/h2]\r\n[p]The student must accept the University Rules and Regulations before proceeding with the final stage of the Registration Process.[/p]\r\n[h2]Step 8      Confirmation Of Details[/h2]\r\n[p]Student confirms that all the details are correct.  Thereafter the student has the option to \"PRINT\" the Registration Form as proof of Registration or to \"FORWARD\" the Registration Form to an email address. [/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-06-01 00:31:41','OnlineRegistration',''),(26,'GUIDE TO COMPLETING TASK REPORTS','[h1][b]Students are required to log onto OLUMS and complete the regular online Task Reports. [/b][/h1]\r\n[p]All learning activities must be recorded on a Task by Task basis. One or more Task Reports can be completed at any one time if the tasks are completely different from each other or if the tasks are linked to different outcomes.[/p]\r\n[h2]1. Each Task or Project Report must be linked to one Specific Outcome. [/h2]\r\n[p]Upon submission of the Task Report, the Mentor and the Academic Assessor will be alerted to assess the Task Report and provide feedback to the student. The student can view all assessments and feedback in real time.[/p]\r\n[p]When a student is confident that he/she had competently achieved any of the desired Outcomes, then the student must indicate this when submitting their Task Reports.[/p]\r\n[h2]2. Task / Project Title[/h2]\r\n[p]Tasks/Projects are a series of learning activities that the student engages with, in order to achieve the desired learning outcomes of the WIL. The duration of a task/project could typically range from 1 day to several weeks. Each task/project must include a Task Title e.g, \"Repaired a 12 Volt Power Supply\" or \" Developed a stepper motor control system using a 8051 Microcontroller\".[/p]\r\n[h2]3. Body of Report\r\n[/h2]\r\n[p]It is commended that the body of the Report should include the following components[/p]\r\n[b]Introduction[/b]\r\n[p]A description of the background of the Task or Project.  This is the \"WHY?\" aspect of the study or activity.  What is the motivation or the reason for the study or activity?[/p]\r\n[b]Procedures and tests[/b]\r\n[p]Describe WHAT you have done in accomplishing the objectives of the tasks/project and HOW you went about doing it, clearly outlining all the steps and procedures that were followed.  [/p]\r\n[p]Ensure that the reports have sufficient detail in order to communicate the Author\'s intent to the reader but, at the same time, not to be over bearing with information overload.  [/p]\r\n[p]Annexures can be uploaded and assigned to the Report.  All documents will be automatically assigned with a reference number starting from Annexure 1. Use this reference number in the Task description.[/p]\r\n[b]Results[/b]\r\n[p]This section shall represent the major element of a report. The results should be discussed in a logical sequence by referring to each individual figure or table. [/p]\r\n[p]Reference every figure and table in the Report.. [/p]\r\n[p]Where applicable, the discussion of the results must represent a critical assessment of the project.[/p]\r\n[b]Conclusions[/b]\r\n[p]Summarize what you have accomplished by emphasizing the important results obtained, and whether you have accomplished the objectives set out for the task or project mentioned in the Introduction. [/p]\r\n[p]The conclusion could include critically analyzing the issues around the project.  Critique your own work if there are deficiencies. [/p]\r\n[p]The question must be asked, Could I have accomplished the same objectives differently?  [/p]\r\n[p]If yes, explain how?[/p]\r\n[p]If no, explain why not?   Explore issues such as costs, efficiency, performance, environment impact, quality, etc.[/p]\r\n[p]Include recommendations to accept or reject the results and to improve the methodology of the project. [/p]\r\n[p]BE CREATIVE. Do not be afraid to express original ideas as long as they make good sense.[/p]\r\n[h2]4. Linking Tasks to Specific Outcomes[/h2]\r\n[p]All Tasks must be linked to a one or more Specific Outcomes.[/p]\r\n[h2]5. Specific Outcome \"COMPLETED\"[/h2]\r\n[p]The student will be prompted to indicate whether the Specific Outcomes had been adequately achieved.[/p]\r\n[p]If the student indicates that he or she is competent to be assessed in any one or more of the Specific Outcomes, the Mentor and the Academic Assessor will be alerted to assess the student\'s performance.[/p]\r\n[h2]6. Uploading of supporting documents[/h2]\r\n[p]Students have the option to scan and upload all supporting documents related to the relevant Task. All Uploaded documents will be automatically referenced as Annexure 1,2,3, etc.[/p]\r\n[b]Work in Progress Tasks[/b]\r\n[p]These are Tasks that are not yet completed at the time of submission of the Progress Report[/p]\r\n[p]Students must flag the Task as Work in Progress via the Menu Button[/p]\r\n[h2]7. Assessment of Progress Reports [/h2]\r\n[p]The assessment rating for each aspect of the assessment ranges from 0 to 100%, O% being extremely poor and 100% being outstanding [/p]\r\n[b]Self Assessment[/b]\r\n[p]On completion of each Task, the student shall conduct a Self Assessment on how he/she thinks had done in completing the Task. Thereafter the Progress Report is submitted. After submission of the Progress Report, the student will not be allowed to edit the Report.[/p]\r\n[b]Industry Mentor Assessment[/b]\r\n[p]After the student submits the Progress Report, the Industry Mentor assigned to the student is alerted via email to Log onto OLUMS and to assess the student\'s performance.[/p]\r\n[b]University Academic Assessment[/b]\r\n[p]After the Industry Mentor assesses the Progress Report and submits the assessment, the University Academic is alerted via email to log onto OLUMS and to assess the student\'s performance. The Academic may add comments.[/p]\r\n[p]The student can view all comments and assessments in real time.[/p]\r\n[h2]8. Work in progress Tasks assessments[/h2]\r\n[p]The Mentor and the University Academic shall have the option to comment on the progress reports of work-in-progress Tasks. [/p]\r\n[b]Calculation of the FINAL Mark[/b]\r\n[p]The Final Mark for the work integrated learning module will calculated as follows:[/p]\r\n[p]1. Each Specific Outcome shall comprise of the average mark of the Industry Mentor, the University Academic[/p][p]Each Specific Outcome shall be weighed by a percentage.[/p]\r\n[p]2. All Core Outcomes must be completed.[/p][p]3. Elective Outcomes[/p][p]If a student completes more than the requisite Electives, then the extra work will be ignored.[/p]\r\n[p]4. Final Marks[/p][p]The Final Mark will be calculated as the sum total of all the weighted marks of each Specific Outcome.[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-19 02:27:40','TASKREPORTS',''),(27,'Working Integrated Learning Assessment','[p]Students are required to log onto and complete regular Progress Reports.[/p][p]All learning activities was be recorded on a Task by Task basis every. A Progress Report may comprise of one or more Task Reports if the tasks are completely different from each other.[/p][p]Each Task Report must be linked to one or more Specific Outcome/s.[/p][p]When the student is confident that the relevant Specific Outcome is completed and ready to be assessed by the Mentor and the Academic Assessor, the student must change the Specific Outcome status to COMPLETED.[/p][p]Upon submission of the Progress Report, the Mentor and the Academic Assessor will be ALERTED to assess the Progress Report and provide feedback comments. The student also performs a self assessment of their progress at the time of completing their Progress Reports. The student can view Mentor and Academic Assessor\'s assessments and feedback comments on the system.[/p][p]Upon submission of the Progress Report, the Mentor and the Academic Assessor will be ALERTED to assess the Progress Report and provide feedback comments. The student also performs a self assessment of their progress at the time of completing their Progress Reports. The student can view Mentor and Academic Assessor\'s assessments and feedback comments on the system.[/p][h1]Progress Report[/h1]\r\n[p]Progress reports will generally comprise of one Task Report. But the student can submit more than one Task Reports if the tasks are significantly different from each other. Each Task Report will have a Task Title.[/p]\r\n[h2]Task Title[/h2]\r\n[p]A Task is a learning activity that the student engages with during the WIL training period. The duration of a task could typically range from 1 day to several weeks. A Task could include the attending of specialized training courses, attending workshop training, practical training, on the job experience, assignments, Design Project, Technical Report writing, etc. Each Task must include Task Title that identifies the Task, eg, \"Repaired a 12 Volt Power Supply\" or \" Attended a 8051 Microcontroller Course\". Each Task will be assigned a unique task number by the system.[/p]\r\n[h2]Task description[/h2]\r\n[p]Under each Task, the students must briefly describe what they had done and how they had gone about doing the tasks in accomplishing the assigned learning activity. The \"WHAT\" aspect will address the introduction to the Task and the \"HOW\" aspect will address the procedures followed in completing the task. A typical Task Report could be between 20 to 60 lines per Task.[/p][h2]Learning experiences[/h2]\r\n[p]Explain what new knowledge, skills or attributes was actually learnt whilst completing the task. The learning experiences may also include an investigation into more efficient and/or cost effective alternative methods of accomplishing the same task. This is important for project type activities.[/p]\r\n[h2]Uploading documents[/h2]\r\n[p]Reference could be made in the Task Report to any diagrams, drawings or documents which could be scanned and uploaded into the system. All scanned documents will be automatically be assigned an Annexure reference number starting from Annexure 1. Use this reference in the Task description.[/p]\r\n[h2]Linking Tasks to Specific Outcomes[/h2]\r\n[p]All Tasks must be linked to one or more of the Specific Outcomes.[/p]\r\n[h2]Specific Outcome \"COMPLETED\"[/h2]\r\n[p]The student will be prompted to indicate when a Specific Outcome is completed and ready for final approval.[/p]\r\n[p]The Mentor and the Academic Assessor will be alerted to approve the Specific Outcome.[/p]\r\n[h2]Uploading of supporting documents[/h2]\r\n[p]Students have the option to scan and upload all supporting documents related to the relevant Task. All Uploaded documents will be automatically referenced as Annexure 1,2,3, etc.[/p]\r\n[h2] Work in Progress Tasks[/h2]\r\n[p]These are Tasks that are not yet completed at the time of submission of the Progress Report[/p]\r\n[p]Students must flag the Task as Work in Progress via the Menu ButtonThe Mentor and the Academic Assessor will only provide Feedback Comments for tasks that are work in progress[/p]\r\n[h1]Assessment Rubric[/h1]\r\n[p]The Assessment Rubric should be scored between 0 and 100 for each category of assessment. A score of 0 will reflect a very low or very poor performance and 100 will reflect an exceptionally high or exceptionally good performance. A typical score of 50 to 80 is a generally a satisfactory to good score.[/p]\r\n',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-06-14 20:44:53','LearningAssessment',''),(28,'Working Integrated Learning Assessment','[p]Mentors and Academic Assessors are required to assess the Student\'s Progress Reports and approve the Specific Outcomes as soon as the student indicates that the Specific Outcome is completed[/p]\r\n[p]Mentors and academic assessors are also required to provide feedback comments to the students to assist to guide their development and progress[/p]\r\n[p]Students will conduct a self assessment of their own performance upon submission of each Progress Report[/p]\r\n[h1]1.      Task Report Assessment[/h1]\r\n[p]The Progress Report of the student must be assessed using the assessment rubric. Each Progress Reports may comprise of one or more Task Reports and each Task Report requires an independent assessment. All the marks allocated to each Task Report will be assigned to the linked Specific Outcome[/p]\r\n[h2] Assessment Rubric[/h2]\r\n[p]The Assessment Rubric should be scored between 0 and 100 for each category of assessment. A score of 0 will reflect a very low or very poor performance and 100 will reflect an exceptionally high or exceptionally good performance. A typical score of 50 to 80 is a generally a satisfactory to good score[/p]\r\n[h2]Work In Progress[/h2]\r\n[p] If the student indicates that a Task is incomplete at the time of completing the Task Report, then the Mentor and Academic Assessor are required to simply provide feedback comments to the students[/p]\r\n[h2]Assessment Deferred[/h2]\r\n[p]If either the Mentors or the Academic Assessor are unable to assess a Task Report for whatever reasons, then the assessment could be deferred to a later date. The Assessment Deferred option should be selected. The reason for deferment can be included in the Feedback Comments. An ACADEMIC ASSESSOR could typically defer an assessment pending a site visit[/p]\r\n[h1]2.       Specific Outcome Assessment and Approval[/h1]\r\n[p] When the students had completed a Specific Outcome, they will indicate that they are ready to be assessed for the respective Specific Outcome. The Mentor and the Academic Assessor will be alerted to assess and approve the Specific Outcome[/p]\r\n[p]The Mentor and the Academic Assessor can exercise the option to defer the approval of the Specific Outcome to a later date.[/p]\r\n[h1]3.       Student Feedback Comments[/h1]\r\n[p]The Mentor and Academic Assessor are required to provide continuous guidance and feedback to the student on their progress during the work integrated learning period to assist them to achieve their full potential[/p]\r\n[list=1][*][p]Comment on the attitude of the student towards the Training Programme[/p][/*][*][p]Comment on the attitude of the student towards his peers and superiors[/p][/*][*][p]General Comments[/p][/*][/list]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-08-03 00:09:48','LearningAssessment1',''),(29,'Working Integrated Learning Assessment','[p] Mentors and academic assessors are also required to provide continuous feedback comments to the students to their progress and to assist and approve the specific outcomes as soon as the student indicates that the specific outcome is ready for assessment[/p][p]Students will conduct a self assessment of their own performance upon submission of each Progress Report[/p][h1]1.Specific Outcome Assessment and Approval[/h1] \r\n[h2]Assessment Rubric[/h2]\r\n[p]The Assessment Rubric should be scored between 0 and 100 for each category of assessment. A score of 0 will reflect a very low or very poor performance and 100 will reflect an exceptionally high or exceptionally good performance. A typical score of 50 to 80 is a generally a satisfactory to good score[/p]\r\n[h2]Assessment Deferred[/h2]\r\n[p]If either the MENTOR or the ACADEMIC ASSESSOR are unable to assess the Specific Outcome for whatever reasons, then the assessment could be deferred to a later date. The ASSESSMENT DEFERRED option should be selected. The reason for deferment can be included in the Feedback Comments. An ACADEMIC ASSESSOR could typically defer an assessment pending a site visit[/p][h2]Assessment Deferred[/h2]\r\n[p]If either the MENTOR or the ACADEMIC ASSESSOR are unable to assess a Task Report for whatever reasons, then the assessment could be deferred to a later date. The ASSESSMENT DEFERRED option should be selected. The reason for deferment can be included in the Feedback Comments. An ACADEMIC ASSESSOR could typically defer an assessment pending a site visit[/p]\r\n[h1]2.Student Feedback Comments[/h1]\r\n[p]The Mentor and Academic Assessor are required to provide continuous guidance and feedback to the student on their progress during the work integrated learning period to assist them to achieve their full potential[/p][list=1][*][p]Comment on the attitude of the student towards the Training Programme[/p][/*][*][p]Comment on the attitude of the student towards his peers and superiors[/p][/*][*][p]General Comments[/p][/*][/list]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-08-03 00:30:05','LearningAssessment2',''),(30,'ABOUT THE SYSTEM','[p]The OLUMS SETA Grant Management and Tracking System manages all aspects of the Management of SETA Grants from a single platform.[/p]\r\n\r\n[p]The System Manages and Tracks the Payment of Stipends to Learners, the Appointment of Host Employers, the Validation of Learner Attendance at Host Employers, the Management of SETA Forms online, Real-time Chat Rooms between Learners, Mentors, University Managers, TVET College Managers, and SETA Managers. [/p]\r\n\r\n[p]University and TVET College Managers are able to monitor and validate the Learners Attendance at the Host Employers and to approve the payment of stipends to Learners via the System[/p]\r\n\r\n[p]Learners are able to complete the Attendance Register and to Submit the Claims Forms online or via their Mobile Apps.  Mentors are also able to use their Mobile App to validate the attendance and Claim Forms of the Learner[/p]\r\n\r\n[p]Executive Reports and AUDIT Trail Reports can be viewed in real-time by the SETA Managers both Locally and Nationally. [/p]\r\n\r\n[p]The Audit Trail includes, the monitoring and tracking of the Grant Funds and quality related issues.[/p]\r\n\r\n[p]It is simple to Manage multiple SETA Grants and multiple Learners from the OLUMS SETA Grant Management platform[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-06-05 01:56:43','instructions_mentor',''),(31,'Instructions To The Student','[p]students have online access to continuously submit progress reports and upload supporting documents, conduct self assessments and provide feedback to mentors and academic assessors. students can view all mentors and academic asessor comments and assessment of task reports[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-06-05 02:03:31','instructions_student',''),(32,'University Policy','[p]The Co-operative Education Department of the University supervises and manages all placement activities between the employer and the student.[/p]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-06-05 01:34:28','UniversityPolicy',''),(33,'Instructions To The Academic','[p]The University appoints an Accademic assessor to monitor and assess students  and assessor is also responsible for approving employer workstation. Accademic assessor also conduct onsite vistation to monitor student performance. The academic assessor performs the following functions  online.[/p]\r\n[list][*]Approval of student work integrated learning registration.[/*][*]assessment of student\'s progress reports and give feedback to students[/*][*]plans onsite vistation schedule[/*][*]completes onsite vistation reports[/*][*]receives work inegrated learning portfolio[/*][*]receives student and mentor feedback report[/*][/list]',0,'','',1,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-06-05 02:27:05','AcademicInstructions',''),(34,'Policy on Institutional Partnering','[h1]PROGRAMMES INSTITUTIONAL PARTNERING[/h1][h2]DECLARATION OF INTENT[/h2][p]It is the policy of the College to:[/p][p](i) engage in partnering arrangements that are beneficial both to the College and to the partnering institution.[/p][h2]OBJECTIVE[/h2][p]The College shall participate in institutional partnering to fulfil one or more of the following objectives:[/p][p](i) to secure additional financial resources for a course, programme or activity.[/p][h2]TERMINOLOGY[/h2][p]For the purposes of this policy, the following definitions apply:[/p][p]Partnering: is based upon mutual interest and a clear understanding, agreement or contract that sets out the objectives and terms of the arrangement.[/p][h2]SCOPE OF APPLICATION[/h2][p]This policy applies to the Principal of Goldfields FET College and the Divisional Manager:[/p][p]Institutional Development who shall be jointly responsible for negotiating, establishing and maintaining partnering arrangements.[/p][h2]GOVERNING PRESCRIPT[/h2][h2]GUIDING PRINCIPLES[/h2][p]In any partnering activity, the following factors shall be considered:[/p][p](i) the shared or compatible objectives inherent in every partnering arrangement. [/p][p](ii) the identity good fit and good character of each proposed partner.[/p]\r\n[h2]PROCEDURES[/h2][h3]T RANSVERSAL[/h3][p](i) The risks in partnering are best controlled by careful design of and commitment to the formal arrangement, careful choice of other parties, clear understanding of roles and responsibilities and attentive management of the relationship. Staff with[/p][p]partnering responsibilities should:[/p][p]have the skills and tools to verify that all potential partners are acceptable in terms of overall institutional and government policies.[/p]\r\n[h2]ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES[/h2][h3]PRINCIPAL[/h3][p]The Principal is responsible for:[/p][p](i) delegating the appropriate authority to the Divisional Manager: Institutional Development to negotiate arrangements with suitable institutions[/p][p](ii) reporting to the Council on the progress of partnering arrangements.[/p][h2]REVIEW[/h2][p]This policy shall be reviewed on an annual basis.[/p]\r\n[p]For More Information [link=/index/download-document/ajax/2/type/1/cms_id/policy_institutional_partnering] [b]Download[/b][/link][/p]',0,'','/documents/policy_on_institutional_partering.pdf',1,'2015-06-16 15:44:02','2011-06-27 02:25:40','policy_institutional_partnering',''),(35,'Policy On Student Experiential Training','[h1]ADMINISTRATION AND MANAGEMENT OF STUDENT EXPERIENTIAL TRAINING[/h1][p]This Policy has been issued on the authority of the Principal of Goldfields FET College[/p][h2]DECLARATION OF INTENT\r\n[/h2][p]The purpose of experiential training or off-site practicals is to provide students with the opportunity to apply what they are learning, or have learnt, in their College course(s) or programme(s) to real world situations. It offers them the chance to work in a business choosing under the supervision of organisation management and/or staff, who will also train and evaluate them.[/p][p]The aims of experiential training are to: [/p][p]allow students an opportunity to consolidate their theoretical foundation through practical experience. A major component of this experience is the formation of a professional attitude.[/p][p]allow students to develop their personality and capacity to adapt to, and handle, challenging situations. The students shall be expected to enhance the following skills during the period of training:[/p][p]communications skills[/p][p]interpersonal skills[/p][p]technical skills[/p][p]teamwork skills[/p][p]management skills[/p][p]problem-solving skills.[/p][p]help students explore their interest in possible careers.[/p][p]The College is committed to ensuring that experiential training represents a quality experience that involves the performance of meaningful activities under the direct supervision of an administrator or manager within the external business. Students should not be involved in tasks that do not support and augment their relevant learning areas - they should only be engaged in activities that they would perform upon qualifying.[/p][h2]Objective\r\n[/h2][p]The objective of this policy is to:[/p][p]establish procedural requirements for experiential training to ensure access, applicability, and appropriate assessment.[/p][p]provide guidelines regarding the administration and assessment of experiential training.[/p][h2]TERMINOLOGY[/h2][p]For the purposes of this policy, the following definitions apply:[/p][p]Co-operative training is an educational or training method that combines study on campus with work experience off campus. Co-operative education programmes comprise periods of study at the Goldfields FET College during which external institutions and/or person can be included, together with periods of experiential training. The work areas shall be as closely related to the study of the students as possible.[/p][p]Experiential training any practical application of the course or programme undertaken by a student within a structured organisational environment that includes formal mentoring and assessment.[/p][h2]SCOPE OF APPLICATION[/h2][p]This policy applies to all the registered students at the College who are participating, or intend to participate, in experiential training to enhance the practical application of their course or programme theory. It also applies to the lecturers who assume the role of ?????????Ñ???«???????????????Â??«?????í???«?????????Â??º??¼?????Â??«?????supervisor?????????Ñ???«???????????????Â??«?????í???«?????????Â??º??ú???«???? during the process.[/p][p]The policy applies to the entire process of experiential training administration, the actual training, assessment and recording.[/p][h2]GOVERNING PRESCRIPTS[/h2][h3]LEGISLATION[/h3][p]The South African Constitution, 1996[/p][p]Skills Development Act, 1998[/p][p]Skills Development Levy Act, 1998[/p][p]South African Qualifications Act, 1995[/p][h3]COLLEGE PRESCRIPTS[/h3][p]GFC-02-2001: Policy on Administration and Control of College Records [/p][p]??????????Ñ?????Â??«?????í??????Â??º??ú???«???¡?????????Ñ?????Â??«?????í??????Â??º??ú???«???¡ ?????????Ñ?????Â??«?????í??????Â??º??ú???«???¡GFC-06-6003: Policy on Student Evaluation and Testing[/p][h2]GUIDING PRINCIPLES[/h2][h3]GENERAL[/h3][p](i)Applicable experiential training is training where a student is expected to: [/p][p]make a deliberate application of his/her academic knowledge and skills. [/p][p]continue to learn as stimulated by the problems and issues encountered. [/p][p]grow in his/her personal maturity and in confidence in his/her own ability. [/p][p]develop empathy with and understanding of persons, groups, and settings typically not encountered on campus.[/p]\r\n[h2]PROCEDURES [/h2]\r\n[h3]REGISTRATION PROCESS\r\n[/h3]\r\n[p](i) The heads of department shall identify the students who must undergo experiential training and inform the relevant student counsellors and campus managers.[/p][h2]ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES[/h2][p]The specific roles in the experiential training process are defined in the section above. It is, however, the overall responsibility of the Vice Principal: Academic Affairs, together with the campus managers, to ensure that experiential training programmes are appropriately established and managed for the benefit of the students.[/p][h2]REVIEW[/h2][p]This policy shall be reviewed on an annual basis.[/p]\r\n[p]For More Information [link=/index/download-document/ajax/2/type/1/cms_id/policy_student_experiential_training][b]Download[/b][/link][/p]',0,'','/documents/policy_on_student_experiental_training.doc',1,'2015-06-16 15:48:50','2015-06-16 04:28:18','policy_student_experiential_training',''),(36,'seta fo